    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "hey i'm struggling with scope creep in my current software project. stakeholders keep asking for \"small tweaks\" mid-sprint and it's ruining our velocity. any professional ways to handle this or stop it from happening?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Scope creep can be a real challenge in software development. You can't let the stakeholders' requests get too far ahead of the project's original plan, or it'll be like trying to catch a slippery fish in a barrel. One approach is to establish a clear understanding of the project's goals and objectives from the start, and then communicate these to the stakeholders. You can also use a \"parking lot\" approach, where you acknowledge the request and agree to discuss it later, but not commit to it until the next sprint review. This helps to keep the stakeholders engaged without compromising the project's velocity.",
      "source": "target",
