    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "that makes sense but even with that wording, they still try to sneak things in. they call it \"just a minor adjustment\" or \"one small thing\" so it doesn't feel like it's officially \"in scope.\" how can i prevent this kind of creep from happening in the first place?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "That's a clever tactic, isn't it? To prevent scope creep, it's essential to have a clear and concise project charter that outlines the project's objectives, scope, and deliverables. This document should be signed off by all stakeholders, including the project sponsor, and should include a clear statement of what is and isn't included in the project. You can also use a \" scope statement\" that outlines the specific requirements and boundaries of the project, and have stakeholders sign off on it before the project starts. This can help prevent those \"minor adjustments\" from creeping in.",
      "source": "target",
